-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 6: evaluate generate-proof-sketch (soft cell, LLM)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { generate-proof-sketch }
-- This is the NP-hard creative work: constructing a correctness argument.

⊢ generate-proof-sketch
  given rewrite-code→code-text' ≡ "def binary_search(arr, target): ..."
  given generate-property-tests→properties ≡ [8 properties]
  given spec→preconditions ≡ "arr is sorted in ascending order, no duplicates"
  yield proof-sketch, invariants[], termination-argument

  ∴ Generate a formal proof sketch for binary_search correctness...

-- LLM evaluation (simulated):

  yield invariants ≡ [
    "INV1 (loop invariant): At the start of each iteration, if target ∈ arr[0..n-1], then target ∈ arr[lo..hi]. Equivalently: target ∉ arr[0..lo-1] ∧ target ∉ arr[hi+1..n-1].",
    "INV2 (bounds): 0 ≤ lo ≤ hi + 1 ≤ n at loop entry (where n = len(arr)).",
    "INV3 (midpoint): lo ≤ mid ≤ hi, so arr[mid] is always a valid access."
  ]

  yield termination-argument ≡ "The quantity (hi - lo + 1) is a natural number that strictly decreases each iteration. Initially hi - lo + 1 ≤ n. Each branch either returns (terminating) or reduces the search space: lo ← mid + 1 increases lo by ≥ 1, hi ← mid - 1 decreases hi by ≥ 1. Since mid = lo + (hi - lo) // 2, we have lo ≤ mid ≤ hi, so mid + 1 > lo and mid - 1 < hi. Thus hi - lo + 1 decreases by ≥ 1 per iteration. When hi - lo + 1 < 1 (i.e., lo > hi), the while condition fails and the loop terminates."

  yield proof-sketch ≡ "
    THEOREM: binary_search(arr, target) returns the index i such that
    arr[i] = target, or -1 if target ∉ arr.

    PRECONDITION: arr is sorted ascending with no duplicates.

    PROOF:

    Step 1 — Initialization:
      lo = 0, hi = len(arr) - 1.
      INV1 holds vacuously: arr[0..lo-1] = arr[0..-1] = ∅, and
      arr[hi+1..n-1] = arr[n..n-1] = ∅, so no elements are excluded.
      INV2 holds: lo = 0 ≤ hi + 1 = n when arr non-empty; when arr empty,
      lo = 0 > hi = -1, loop doesn't execute, returns -1 correctly.

    Step 2 — Maintenance (found case):
      If arr[mid] = target, return mid.
      Correctness: arr[mid] = target by direct comparison. Since arr has
      no duplicates, mid is the unique index. ∎

    Step 3 — Maintenance (target > arr[mid]):
      arr[mid] < target, so set lo = mid + 1.
      Since arr is sorted: ∀ j ∈ [lo..mid], arr[j] ≤ arr[mid] < target.
      So target ∉ arr[lo..mid]. Combined with INV1 (target ∉ arr[0..lo-1]),
      we get target ∉ arr[0..mid]. New lo = mid + 1 preserves INV1.

    Step 4 — Maintenance (target < arr[mid]):
      arr[mid] > target, so set hi = mid - 1.
      Since arr is sorted: ∀ j ∈ [mid..hi], arr[j] ≥ arr[mid] > target.
      So target ∉ arr[mid..hi]. Combined with INV1 (target ∉ arr[hi+1..n-1]),
      we get target ∉ arr[mid..n-1]. New hi = mid - 1 preserves INV1.

    Step 5 — Termination (not-found case):
      Loop exits when lo > hi. By INV1: target ∉ arr[0..lo-1] and
      target ∉ arr[hi+1..n-1]. Since lo > hi, these ranges cover
      arr[0..n-1] entirely. Therefore target ∉ arr. Return -1. ∎

    Step 6 — Termination argument:
      Variant function V = hi - lo + 1. V ∈ ℕ at loop entry (since
      lo ≤ hi implies V ≥ 1). Each non-returning branch decreases V by ≥ 1.
      V = 0 ⟹ lo > hi ⟹ loop exits. Therefore the loop terminates.

    Step 7 — Precondition usage:
      Steps 3 and 4 use 'arr is sorted' to conclude that elements
      on one side of mid are all < or > target. Without sortedness,
      arr[mid] < target would NOT imply arr[lo..mid-1] < target, and
      the search space reduction would be invalid.

    QED.
  "

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ proof-sketch contains at least 4 logical steps → ✓ (7 steps)
--   ⊨ invariants includes loop invariant referencing lo, hi, target → ✓ (INV1)
--   ⊨ termination-argument identifies decreasing quantity bounded below → ✓ (hi - lo + 1, bounded by 0)

