-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- EXECUTION SUMMARY
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
--
-- Total frames: 9 (0-8)
-- ⊢∘ iterations: 1 (code was correct on first generation — no rewrites needed)
-- Cells evaluated: spec, generate-code, generate-property-tests, run-tests,
--   analyze-failures, rewrite-code, generate-proof-sketch, verify-proof,
--   proof-certificate
-- Crystallized cells: 1 (verify-proof — ran without LLM)
-- Soft cells: 7 (required LLM simulation)
-- Pass-through cells: 1 (spec)
--
-- Input: 1 natural language specification
-- Output: proof-carrying certificate with code, tests, and formal proof
-- Tests: 12/12 passing across 8 properties
-- Proof: 7-step argument verified by crystallized checker
-- Confidence: HIGH
--
-- Key observations:
--
-- ⊢= Observation 1: proof-carrying computation separates generation from verification
--   The LLM generated code (frame 1) and a proof (frame 6) — both creative,
--   NP-hard tasks requiring search through a large space of possible outputs.
--   The crystallized verifier (frame 7) checked the proof structurally in P-time
--   without calling the LLM. This is Cell's killer pattern: the LLM finds
--   solutions, the verifier certifies them. Neither trusts the other — the
--   verifier catches wrong proofs, and the LLM doesn't know what the verifier
--   will check. Adversarial separation produces trustworthy computation.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 2: the ⊢∘ evolution loop is a test-driven development cycle
--   generate-code → run-tests → analyze-failures → rewrite-code is exactly
--   the red-green-refactor cycle. When tests fail, the LLM analyzes WHY (not
--   just retrying blindly) and applies targeted fixes. The evolution loop
--   embeds software engineering methodology in the language itself. In this
--   trace, the code passed on iteration 1 — but the mechanism for iterative
--   repair was ready. A deliberately buggy initial implementation (e.g., using
--   mid = (lo + hi) / 2 causing overflow) would trigger the full cycle.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 3: crystallization boundary is exactly the P/NP boundary
--   verify-proof is crystallized (⊢=) because checking a proof is in P.
--   generate-code and generate-proof-sketch are soft (∴) because generating
--   correct code and proofs is NP-hard. This isn't coincidence — it's the
--   fundamental asymmetry that makes proof-carrying computation work. Easy
--   to check, hard to create. Cell's crystallization spectrum maps directly
--   onto computational complexity classes.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 4: the oracle system provides layered assurance
--   Three layers of evidence support the code's correctness:
--   (1) Property tests — empirical evidence (12 concrete test cases)
--   (2) Proof sketch — deductive evidence (7-step logical argument)
--   (3) Proof verification — meta-evidence (crystallized checker confirms
--       the proof has all required components). Each layer catches different
--   failure modes: tests catch bugs, proofs catch logical gaps, verification
--   catches incomplete proofs. This is defense in depth applied to correctness.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 5: generate-code and generate-property-tests are confluent
--   In frame 1 and 2, both cells were in the ready set simultaneously.
--   They depend only on spec (frozen in frame 0), not on each other.
--   Confluence guarantees we'd get the same result evaluating them in either
--   order — or in parallel. The test cases are generated independently of the
--   code, ensuring they're not biased by the implementation. This independence
--   is both a confluence property AND a testing best practice: the oracle
--   (tests) shouldn't know how the implementation works.
